# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The **American Society of Civil Engineers** (**ASCE**) is a tax-exempt professional body founded in 1852 to represent members of the civil engineering profession worldwide.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Headquartered in Reston, Virginia, it is the oldest national engineering society in the United States.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Its constitution was based on the older Boston Society of Civil Engineers from 1848.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] ASCE is dedicated to the advancement of the science and profession of civil engineering and the enhancement of human welfare through the activities of society members.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] It has more than 143,000 members in 177 countries.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Its mission is to provide essential value to members, their careers, partners, and the public; facilitate the advancement of technology; encourage and provide the tools for lifelong learning; promote professionalism and the profession; develop and support civil engineers.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The first serious and documented attempts to organize civil engineers as a professional society in the newly created United States were in the early 19th century.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Later, in 1834, an American trade periodical, the "American Railroad Journal," advocated for a similar national organization of civil engineers.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] On December 17, 1838, a petition started circulating asking civil engineers to meet in 1839 in Baltimore, Maryland, to organize a permanent society of civil engineers.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Prior to that, thirteen notable civil engineers largely identifiable as being from New York, Pennsylvania, or Maryland met in Philadelphia.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Forty engineers actually appeared at the February 1839 meeting in Baltimore, including J.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Edgar Thomson (Future Chief Engineer and later President of the Pennsylvania Railroad), Wright, Roberts, Edward Miller, and the Maryland engineers Isaac Trimble and Benjamin Henry Latrobe II and attendees from as far as Massachusetts, Illinois, and Louisiana.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Miller later ascribed the failure to the difficulties of assembling members due to available means for traveling in the country at the time.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] That journal continued discussion on forming an engineers' organization from 1839 thru 1843 serving its own self-interests in advocating its journal as a replacement for a professional society but to no avail.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] During the 1840s, professional organizations continued to develop and organize in the United States.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] During this same period of association incorporations in the 1840s, attempts were again made at organizing an American engineer association.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] They succeeded at first with the Boston Society of Civil Engineers, organized in 1848, and then in October 1852, with an effort to organize a Society of Civil Engineers and Architects in New York.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Craven, Chief Engineer of the Croton Aqueduct and future ASCE president, the meeting resolved to incorporate the society under the name "American Society of Civil Engineers And Architects".
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The founding meeting was held on November 5, 1852, in the offices of the Croton Aqueduct Department at the Rotunda in City Hall Park, Manhattan.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Membership eligibility was restricted to "civil, geological, mining and mechanical Engineers, architects, and other persons who, by profession, are interested in the advancement of science." James Laurie was elected the society's first president.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] At an early meeting of the Board of Direction in 1852, instructions were given for the incorporation of the "American Society of Civil Engineers and Architects" but this was the proper steps were never taken, and therefore this name never legally belonged to the association.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The ASCE held its first meetings at the Croton Aqueduct Department building in City Hall Park.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The meetings only went through 1855 and with the advent of the American Civil War, the society suspended its activities.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The next meeting was more than twelve years later in 1867.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] A number of the original founders, such as James Laurie, J.W.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Talcott, were at this meeting and were dedicated to the objective of resuscitating the society.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] They also planned to put the society on a more permanent footing and elect fifty-four new members.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] With success in that effort, the young engineering society passed a resolution noting that its preservation was mainly due to the persevering efforts of its first president, James Laurie.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The address of President James Pugh Kirkwood delivered at that meeting in 1867 was the first publication of the society, appearing in Volume 1 of *Transactions*, bearing date of 1872.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] On March 4, 1868, by a vote of 17 to 4, the name was changed to "American Society of Civil Engineers", but it was not until April 17, 1877, that the lack of incorporation was discovered and the proper steps taken to remedy the defect.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The society was then chartered and incorporated in New York state.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The reconvened ASCE met at the Chamber of Commerce of the State of New York until 1875 when the society moved to 4 East 23rd Street.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The ASCE moved again in 1877 to 104 East 20th Street and in 1881 to 127 East 23rd Street.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The ASCE commissioned a new headquarters at 220 West 57th Street in 1895.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The building was completed in 1897 and served as the society's headquarters until 1917 when the ASCE moved to the Engineering Societies' Building.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Nora Stanton Barney was among the first women in the United States to earn a civil engineering degree, graduating from Cornell University in 1905.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] In the same year, she was accepted as a junior member of the organization and began work for the New York City Board of Water Supply.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] She was the first female member of ASCE, where she was allowed to be a junior member, but was denied advancement to associate member in 1916 because of her gender.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] In 2015, she was posthumously advanced to ASCE Fellow status.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] ASCE's headquarters relocated to the Engineering Societies' Building in 1917; additional floors were added on top of the building to accommodate the society's new offices.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The weight of the extra stories could not be supported on the existing pilings, so four new steel columns were constructed through the structure, supported directly on the bedrock.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] In 1961, ASCE's headquarters moved from the Engineering Societies' Building to the United Engineering Center, a new skyscraper built for twenty different engineering societies across from the headquarters of the United Nations.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] In 1996, ASCE relocated its headquarters from New York City to Reston, Virginia.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The relocation to the Washington metropolitan area was made to bring ASCE's headquarters closer to the legislative branch of the federal government and also reduced operating costs.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] In 1999, the ASCE elected the top-ten "civil engineering achievements that had the greatest positive impact on life in the 20th century" in "broad categories".
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Monuments of the Millennium were a "combination of technical engineering achievement, courage and inspiration, and a dramatic influence on the development of [their] communities".
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] ASCE stated that dissemination of technical and professional information to the civil engineering profession was a major goal of the society.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] They also publish an online bibliographic database, conference proceedings, standards, manuals of practice, and technical reports.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The ASCE Library contains 470+ e-books and standards, some with chapter-level access and no restrictive DRM, and 600+ online proceedings.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Each year, more than 55,000 engineers earn continuing education units (CEUs) and/or professional development hours (PDHs) by participating in ASCE's continuing education programs.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] ASCE hosts more than 15 annual and specialty conferences, over 200 continuing education seminars and more than 300 live web seminars.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Meetings include "...committees, task forces, focus groups, workshops and seminars designed to bring together civil engineering experts either from specific fields or those with a broad range of experience and skills.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The engineering programs division directly advances the science of engineering by delivering technical content for ASCE's publications, conferences and continuing education programs.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] It consists of eight discipline-specific institutes, four technical divisions, and six technical councils.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The work is accomplished by over 600 technical committees with editorial responsibility for 28 of ASCE's 33 journals.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] On an annual basis, the division conducts more than twelve congresses and specialty conferences.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] As a founding society of ANSI and accredited standards development organization, ASCE committees use an established and audited process to produce consensus standards under a program supervised by the society's Codes and Standards Committee.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] (CEC), affiliated with ASCE, has been established to support specialty certification academies for civil engineering specialties and is accredited by the Council of Engineering and Scientific Specialty Boards (CESB).
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] CEC also handles safety certification for state, municipal, and federal buildings, formerly the province of the now-defunct Building Security Council.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The Committee on Critical Infrastructure (CCI) provides vision and guidance on ASCE activities related to critical infrastructure resilience, including planning, design, construction, O&M, and event mitigation, response and recovery.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Certification is the recognition of attaining advanced knowledge and skills in a specialty area of civil engineering.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] ASCE offers certifications for engineers who demonstrate advanced knowledge and skills in their area of engineering.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Michel Award for Industry Advancement of Research and the Charles Pankow Award for innovation, 12 scholarships and fellowships for student members.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Created in 1968 by ASCE's Sanitary Engineering Division, the Wesley W.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Horner award is named after former ASCE President Wesley W.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Horner, and given to a recently peer reviewed published paper in the fields of hydrology, urban drainage, or sewerage.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Special consideration is given to private practice engineering work that is recognized as a valuable contribution to the field of environmental engineering.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The Lifetime Achievement Award has been presented annually since 1999 and recognizes five different individual leaders.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] One award is present in each category of design, construction, government, education, and management.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] In July 1946, the Board of Direction authorized annual awards on recommendation by the society's Committee on Research to stimulate research in civil engineering.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Alberta Reed Huber endowed these prizes in honor of her husband, Walter L.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The Huber Prize is considered the highest level mid-career research prize in civil engineering and is awarded for outstanding achievements and contributions in research with respect to all disciplines of civil engineering.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The LTPP International Data Analysis Contest is an annual data analysis contest held by the ASCE in collaboration with the Federal Highway Administration (FHWA).
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The participants utilize Long-Term Pavement Performance Program (LTPP) data as part of their analysis.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] At the instigation of the former students of Nathan Mortimore Newmark, the Nathan M.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Newmark Medal was established in 1975 by the Engineering Mechanics Institute and Structural Engineering Institute of the American Society of Civil Engineers (ASCE) in honor of his contributions in structural engineering and mechanics.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The medal is given to an ASCE member whose outstanding contributions in structural mechanics have substantially strengthened the scientific base of structural engineering, documented in the form of papers or other written presentations.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Nominations are made once a year and due on November 1.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The foundation board of directors has seven persons and its bylaws require that four of the seven directors must be ASCE officers as well and the ASCE executive director and chief financial officer must also be ASCE employees.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The foundation's support is most often to ASCE's charitable, educational and scientific programs.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The foundation's largest program is supporting three strategic areas; lifelong learning and leadership, advocacy for infrastructure investment and the role of civil engineers in sustainable practices.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] In 2014, this foundation's support in these areas was almost US$4 million.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] ASCE provides peer reviews at the request of public agencies and projects as a "means to improve the management and quality of [public agency] services and thus better protect the public health and safety with which they are entrusted".
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] After the 2005 levee failures in Greater New Orleans, the commander of the U.S.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Lawrence Roth, deputy executive director of the ASCE led the ERP development, served as the panel's chief of staff and facilitated its interaction with IPET.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The expert panel's role was to provide an independent technical review of the IPET's activities and findings, as stated at a National Research Council meeting in New Orleans: "an independent review panel ensure[s] that the outcome is a robust, credible and defensible performance evaluation".
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Gen Strock gave all expert review panel members an Outstanding Civilian Service Medals.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] On June 1, 2007, the ASCE issued its expert review panel report, and an accompanying press release.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The corps acknowledged receiving a copy of the letter and refused to comment until the ASCE's Committee on Professional Conduct (CPC) had commented on the complaint.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] It took over a year for the ASCE to announce the results of the CPC.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] On November 14, 2007, ASCE announced that U.S.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] (ret), would lead an independent task force of outside experts to review how ASCE participated in engineering studies of national significance.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] ASCE President David Mongan said the review was to address criticism of ASCE´s role in assisting the Army Corps of Engineers-sponsored investigation of Katrina failures.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Mongan assured citizens of metro New Orleans in a letter to the *Times Picayune*, that ASCE took "this matter very seriously and that appropriate actions are being taken".
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The panel recommended in results released on September 12, 2008, that ASCE should immediately take steps to remove the potential for conflict of interest in its participation in post-disaster engineering studies.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] It concluded that ASCE should draw up an ethics policy to eliminate questions of possible conflicts of interest.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] On April 6, 2009, an internal probe with the ASCE issued a report that ordered a retraction of the ASCE's June 1, 2007, press release.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] On November 5, 2007, New Orleans–based grassroots group *Levees.org* led by Sandy Rosenthal criticized the ASCE's close relationship with the United States Army Corps of Engineers in a spoof online public service announcement.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] On November 12, 2007, the ASCE asked Levees.org to remove the video from the internet, threatening the organization with legal action if it did not comply.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] On November 13, the Times-Picayune posted the video on its website.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] In March 2008, Levees.org announced that records obtained under the Freedom of Information Act revealed that as early October 2005, the Army Corps of Engineers had directed and later paid the ASCE more than $1.1 million for its peer review (Grant Number: W912HZ-06-1-0001).
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The grant also paid for a series of misleading ASCE presentations attempting to shift blame away from the corps and onto local levee officials.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Members of the ASCE are forbidden from making false or exaggerated statements and also from making statements for an interested party unless this is disclosed.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Levees.org claimed the records showed how the external peer review would be done in four phases: Phase 1 was research and analysis on the performance of the levees, floodwalls and other important structures.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Phase 2 was provision of information on the current system to prevent future flooding.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Phase 3 was provision of information to evaluate alternative approaches to flood protection.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Phase 4 was transfer information and knowledge gained to a broader audience within Corps and its consultancy community to communicate lessons learned.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The group claimed that these records were proof that ASCE's routine powerpoint presentation from 2007 and 2008 were a public relations campaign to repair the corps' reputation.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-civil-engineers] ASCE officials responded that ASCE paid for the powerpoint presentations itself and had not used USACE grant money for that purpose.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] Founded as an engineering society focused on mechanical engineering in North America, ASME is today multidisciplinary and global.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME has over 85,000 members in more than 135 countries worldwide.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME was founded in 1880 in response to numerous steam boiler pressure vessel failures by Alexander Lyman Holley, Henry Rossiter Worthington, John Edison Sweet and Matthias N.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] Forney, with Robert Henry Thurston as the society's founding president.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] Known for setting codes and standards for mechanical devices, ASME conducts one of the world's largest technical publishing operations.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] It holds numerous technical conferences and hundreds of professional development courses each year and sponsors numerous outreach and educational programs.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] Ned Djilali and Georgia Tech president and woman engineer supporter Blake R Van Leer were executive members.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] Kate Gleason and Lydia Weld were the first two women members.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME is one of the oldest standards-developing organizations in America.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] It produces approximately 600 codes and standards covering many technical areas, such as fasteners, plumbing fixtures, elevators, pipelines, and power plant systems and components.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME's standards are developed by committees of subject matter experts using an open, consensus-based process.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] Many ASME standards are cited by government agencies as tools to meet their regulatory objectives.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME standards are therefore voluntary, unless the standards have been incorporated into a legally binding business contract or incorporated into regulations enforced by an authority having jurisdiction, such as a federal, state, or local government agency.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME's standards are used in more than 100 countries and have been translated into numerous languages.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] The largest ASME standard, both in size and in the number of volunteers involved in its preparation, is the ASME Boiler and Pressure Vessel Code (BPVC).
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] The BPVC provides rules for the design, fabrication, installation, inspection, care, and use of boilers, pressure vessels, and nuclear components.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] The code also includes standards on materials, welding and brazing procedures and qualifications, nondestructive examination, and nuclear in-service inspection.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] In addition to academic journals, since 1880 the ASME has also published the magazine *Mechanical Engineering*.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] This means the nominees need not be professional educators.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] (1879–1964), an ASME Member and professor of mechanical engineering and head of the department at the Polytechnic Institute of Brooklyn, established the Medal.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME runs several annual E-Fests, or Engineering Festivals, taking the place of the Student Professional Development Conference (SPDC) series.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] In addition to the Human Powered Vehicle Challenge (HPVC), the Innovative Additive Manufacturing 3D Challenge (IAM3D), the Student Design Competition, and the Old Guard Competition, there are also talks, interactive workshops, and entertainment.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] These events allows students to network with working engineers, host contests, and promote ASME's benefits to students as well as professionals.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] E-Fests are held in four regions in the United States and internationally—western U.S, eastern U.S., Asia Pacific, and South America—with the E-Fest location for each region changing every year.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME holds a variety of competitions every year for engineering students from around the world.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME has four key offices in the United States, including its headquarters operation in New York, N.Y., and three international offices in Beijing, China; Brussels, Belgium, and New Delhi, India.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME has two institutes and 32 technical divisions within its organizational structure.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] In 1982, ASME was found to be the first non-profit organization to in violation of the Sherman Antitrust Act.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] The United States Supreme Court found the organization liable for more than $6 million in *American Society of Mechanical Engineers v.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems] The ***ASCE-ASME Journal of Risk and Uncertainty in Engineering Systems*** is a peer-reviewed scientific journal established in 2014 by the American Society of Civil Engineers (ASCE) and the American Society of Mechanical Engineers (ASME).
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems] It disseminates research findings, best practices concerns, and discussions and debates on risk- and uncertainty-related issues in the areas of civil and mechanical engineering and related fields.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems] The journal covers risk and uncertainty issues in planning, design, construction/manufacturing, utilization, decommissioning and removal, and evaluation of engineering systems.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems] As of 2018, it is the only joint journal for both societies with another society in their respective long histories.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems] ASCE and ASME registered the two parts as separate journals as Part A and Part B, respectively, to facilitate the production of the journal along other journals offered by the respective societies.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems] Both journals have the same editorial board and leadership and produced their first quarterly issues at the end of first quarter of 2015.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems] The current Editor-in-Chief of the two journals is Professor Michael Beer.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems] Both Part A and Part B are listed in the Emerging Sources Citation Index by Clarivate Analytics, formerly Thomson Reuters, and it is eligible for indexing in 2018.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems] From 2016 onward, all articles are included in Web of Science.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems] The current Impact Factor of Part A is 2.4, for Part B it's 2.1. based on the latest Journal Citation Reports released by Clarivate Analytics.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/bilal-m-ayyub] Ayyub was born in Tulkarm, Palestine, 5 January 1958 and moved to Kuwait in 1961.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/bilal-m-ayyub] He was K12 schooled in Kuwait, and earned a Bachelors of Science in Civil Engineering from Kuwait University in 1980.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/bilal-m-ayyub] He received both a Masters of Science in Civil Engineering (1981) and a Doctorate of Philosophy (1983) from the Georgia Institute of Technology.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/bilal-m-ayyub] He works in the areas of risk analysis, uncertainty modeling, decision analysis, and systems engineering.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/bilal-m-ayyub] His specialty is risk and uncertainty analysis for decision and policy making including climate adaptation.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/bilal-m-ayyub] Ayyub provides advisory services as needed through BMA Engineering, Inc., a Bethesda, Maryland-based engineering consulting firm that works with infrastructure and defense systems.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/bilal-m-ayyub] Ayyub is the founding editor-in-chief of the ASCE-ASME *Journal of Risk and Uncertainty in Engineering Systems* in its two parts: Part A.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/bilal-m-ayyub] He is also on the editorial board of the *Journal of Risk Analysis* and the *Journal of Ship Research* of the SNAME.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/bilal-m-ayyub] He is the author or co-author of more than 600 publications in journals and conference proceedings, and reports.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/civil-engineering] Civil engineering is traditionally broken into a number of sub-disciplines.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/civil-engineering] It is considered the second-oldest engineering discipline after military engineering, and it is defined to distinguish non-military engineering from military engineering.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/civil-engineering] Civil engineering can take place in the public sector from municipal public works departments through to national government agencies, and in the private sector from locally based firms to *Fortune* Global 500 companies.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/civil-engineering] Civil engineering is the application of physical and scientific principles for solving the problems of society, and its history is intricately linked to advances in the understanding of physics and mathematics throughout history.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/civil-engineering] Because civil engineering is a broad profession, including several specialized sub-disciplines, its history is linked to knowledge of structures, materials science, geography, geology, soils, hydrology, environmental science, mechanics, project management, and other fields.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/civil-engineering] Throughout ancient and medieval history most architectural design and construction was carried out by artisans, such as stonemasons and carpenters, rising to the role of master builder.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/civil-engineering] Knowledge was retained in craft guilds and seldom supplanted by advances.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/civil-engineering] Structures, roads, and infrastructure that existed were repetitive, and increases in scale were incremental.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/civil-engineering] Brahmagupta, an Indian mathematician, used arithmetic in the 7th century AD, based on Hindu-Arabic numerals, for excavation (volume) computations.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/civil-engineering] Engineering has been an aspect of life since the beginnings of human existence.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/civil-engineering] The earliest practice of civil engineering may have commenced between 4000 and 2000 BC in ancient Egypt, the Indus Valley civilization, and Mesopotamia (ancient Iraq) when humans started to abandon a nomadic existence, creating a need for the construction of shelter.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/civil-engineering] During this time, transportation became increasingly important leading to the development of the wheel and sailing.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/civil-engineering] Until modern times there was no clear distinction between civil engineering and architecture, and the terms engineer and architect were mainly geographical variations referring to the same occupation, and often used interchangeably.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/civil-engineering] The constructions of pyramids in Egypt (c.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/civil-engineering] 2700–2500 BC) constitute some of the first instances of large structure constructions in history.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/civil-engineering] Other ancient historic civil engineering constructions include the Qanat water management system in modern-day Iran (the oldest is older than 3000 years and longer than 71 kilometres (44 mi)), the Parthenon by Iktinos in Ancient Greece (447–438 BC), the Appian Way by Roman engineers (c.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/civil-engineering] 312 BC), the Great Wall of China by General Meng T'ien under orders from Ch'in Emperor Shih Huang Ti (c.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/civil-engineering] 220 BC) and the stupas constructed in ancient Sri Lanka like the Jetavanaramaya and the extensive irrigation works in Anuradhapura.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/civil-engineering] The Romans developed civil structures throughout their empire, including especially aqueducts, insulae, harbors, bridges, dams and roads.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/civil-engineering] In the 18th century, the term civil engineering was coined to incorporate all things civilian as opposed to military engineering.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/civil-engineering] In 1747, the first institution for the teaching of civil engineering, the École Nationale des Ponts et Chaussées, was established in France; and more examples followed in other European countries, like Spain (Escuela Técnica Superior de Ingenieros de Caminos, Canales y Puertos).
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/civil-engineering] The first self-proclaimed civil engineer was John Smeaton, who constructed the Eddystone Lighthouse.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/civil-engineering] In 1771 Smeaton and some of his colleagues formed the Smeatonian Society of Civil Engineers, a group of leaders of the profession who met informally over dinner.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/civil-engineering] Though there was evidence of some technical meetings, it was little more than a social society.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/civil-engineering] In 1818 the Institution of Civil Engineers was founded in London, and in 1820 the eminent engineer Thomas Telford became its first president.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/civil-engineering] The institution received a Royal Charter in 1828, formally recognising civil engineering as a profession.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/civil-engineering] The first private college to teach civil engineering in the United States was Norwich University, founded in 1819 by Captain Alden Partridge.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/civil-engineering] The first degree in civil engineering in the United States was awarded by Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute in 1835.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/civil-engineering] The first such degree to be awarded to a woman was granted by Cornell University to Nora Stanton Blatch in 1905.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/civil-engineering] In most countries, a bachelor's degree in engineering represents the first step towards professional certification, and a professional body certifies the degree program.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/civil-engineering] After completing a certified degree program, the engineer must satisfy a range of requirements including work experience and exam requirements before being certified.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/civil-engineering] There are international agreements between relevant professional bodies to allow engineers to practice across national borders.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/civil-engineering] The benefits of certification vary depending upon location.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/civil-engineering] No such legislation has been enacted in other countries including the United Kingdom.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/civil-engineering] In Australia, state licensing of engineers is limited to the state of Queensland.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/civil-engineering] Almost all certifying bodies maintain a code of ethics which all members must abide by.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/civil-engineering] Engineers must obey contract law in their contractual relationships with other parties.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/civil-engineering] In cases where an engineer's work fails, they may be subject to the law of tort of negligence, and in extreme cases, criminal charges.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/civil-engineering] An engineer's work must also comply with numerous other rules and regulations such as building codes and environmental law.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/civil-engineering] There are a number of sub-disciplines within the broad field of civil engineering.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/civil-engineering] General civil engineers work closely with surveyors and specialized civil engineers to design grading, drainage, pavement, water supply, sewer service, dams, electric and communications supply.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/civil-engineering] General civil engineering is also referred to as site engineering, a branch of civil engineering that primarily focuses on converting a tract of land from one usage to another.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/civil-engineering] Site engineers spend time visiting project sites, meeting with stakeholders, and preparing construction plans.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/civil-engineering] Civil engineers apply the principles of geotechnical engineering, structural engineering, environmental engineering, transportation engineering and construction engineering to residential, commercial, industrial and public works projects of all sizes and levels of construction.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/civil-engineering] Environmental engineering deals with treatment of chemical, biological, or thermal wastes, purification of water and air, and remediation of contaminated sites after waste disposal or accidental contamination.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/civil-engineering] Among the topics covered by environmental engineering are pollutant transport, water purification, waste water treatment, air pollution, solid waste treatment, recycling, and hazardous waste management.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/civil-engineering] Environmental engineers administer pollution reduction, green engineering, and industrial ecology.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/civil-engineering] Environmental engineers also compile information on environmental consequences of proposed actions.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/civil-engineering] Identification of soil properties presents challenges to geotechnical engineers.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/civil-engineering] Boundary conditions are often well defined in other branches of civil engineering, but unlike steel or concrete, the material properties and behavior of soil are difficult to predict due to its variability and limitation on investigation.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/civil-engineering] Furthermore, soil exhibits nonlinear (stress-dependent) strength, stiffness, and dilatancy (volume change associated with application of shear stress), making studying soil mechanics all the more difficult.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/civil-engineering] Geotechnical engineers frequently work with professional geologists, Geological Engineering professionals and soil scientists.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/civil-engineering] Design considerations will include strength, stiffness, and stability of the structure when subjected to loads which may be static, such as furniture or self-weight, or dynamic, such as wind, seismic, crowd or vehicle loads, or transitory, such as temporary construction loads or impact.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/civil-engineering] Other considerations include cost, constructibility, safety, aesthetics and sustainability.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/civil-engineering] Although surveying is a distinct profession with separate qualifications and licensing arrangements, civil engineers are trained in the basics of surveying and mapping, as well as geographic information systems.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/civil-engineering] Surveyors also lay out the routes of railways, tramway tracks, highways, roads, pipelines and streets as well as position other infrastructure, such as harbors, before construction.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/civil-engineering] In the United States, Canada, the United Kingdom and most Commonwealth countries land surveying is considered to be a separate and distinct profession.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/civil-engineering] Land surveyors are not considered to be engineers, and have their own professional associations and licensing requirements.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/civil-engineering] They collect data on important geological features below and on the land.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/civil-engineering] Construction surveying is generally performed by specialized technicians.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/civil-engineering] Unlike land surveyors, the resulting plan does not have legal status.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/civil-engineering] Civil engineering systems is a discipline that promotes using systems thinking to manage complexity and change in civil engineering within its broader public context.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/civil-engineering] It posits that the proper development of civil engineering infrastructure requires a holistic, coherent understanding of the relationships between all of the crucial factors that contribute to successful projects while at the same time emphasizing the importance of attention to technical detail.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/civil-engineering] Its purpose is to help integrate the entire civil engineering project life cycle from conception, through planning, designing, making, operating to decommissioning.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/clarivate-analytics] Clarivate formed in 2016, following the acquisition of Thomson Reuters' Intellectual Property and Science business by Onex Corporation and Baring Private Equity Asia.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/clarivate-analytics] Since 2016, Clarivate acquired various companies, notably ProQuest in 2021.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/clarivate-analytics] On July 11, 2016, Thomson Reuters a $3.55 billion sale of its Intellectual Property and Science business to private equity firms Onex Corporation and Baring Private Equity Asia.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/clarivate-analytics] The transaction was completed on October 4, 2016, and Clarivate Analytics became an independent company as a corporate spin-off.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/clarivate-analytics] In May 2019, Clarivate merged with the Churchill Capital Corp SPAC to obtain a public listing on the New York Stock Exchange (NYSE), trading under symbol CLVT.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/clarivate-analytics] On March 11, 2022, Clarivate, which has an office in Odesa, Ukraine, announced it would cease all commercial activity in Russia following Russia's full-scale invasion of Ukraine on February 22, 2022.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/clarivate-analytics] As of 2023, Clarivate conducts operations through three strategic business units: Intellectual Property Group, Life Sciences & Healthcare Group, and Academic and Government Group, each led by a president.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/clarivate-analytics] On July 11, 2022, Clarivate announced Jerre Stead's retirement and transition from Executive Chair and CEO to Non-Executive Chair.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/clarivate-analytics] IHS Markit CFO Jonathan Gear joined Clarivate as CEO-elect on July 11, 2022, becoming CEO on September 1, 2022.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/clarivate-analytics] On September 1, 2022, Clarivate announced Jerre Stead's retirement from the Board and appointment as Chair Emeritus effective October 20, 2022.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/clarivate-analytics] On August 6, 2024, Clarivate appointed former ProQuest CEO Matti Shem Tov as CEO.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/clarivate-analytics] As Clarivate acquired ProQuest, various products of ProQuest are being operated under Clarivate, which encompasses products that ProQuest had taken on relatively recently, through acquisitions of its own—notably those of Innovative Interfaces: Vega, Sierra, Polaris, Millennium, and Virtua.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/clarivate-analytics] The Derwent World Patents Index (DWPI) is a database containing patent applications and grants from 44 of the world's patent issuing authorities.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/clarivate-analytics] ScholarOne is a submission management system to allow an editor of an academic journal to manage electronic submission of authors' manuscripts for publication, to recruit reviewers of those manuscripts, to check authors' compliance with the journal's requirements, and to communicate with authors.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/clarivate-analytics] It was sold to the American software company Silverchair in 2024.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/clarivate-analytics] Clarivate publishes an annual Highly Cited Researchers list.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/clarivate-analytics] The 2019 list of Highly Cited Researchers was released on November 19, 2019.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/clarivate-analytics] Clarivate Citation Laureates, formerly Thomson Reuters Citation Laureates, is a list of candidates considered likely to win the Nobel Prize in their respective field.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/clarivate-analytics] The candidates are so named based on the citation impact of their published research.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/clarivate-analytics] Thomson Reuters Citation Laureates was established in 1989.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/clarivate-analytics] The list pertains to likely Nobel Prize winners in medicine, chemistry, physics, and economics.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/clarivate-analytics] There appears to be a correlation between high citation rates for a published researcher and the award of prestigious accolades.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/clarivate-analytics] Furthermore, citation rates disclose researchers furnishing instrumental contributions that advance the science of their respective field.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/clarivate-analytics] Finally, choosing one tenth of one percent (0.1%) of the highest impact papers winnows the analysis to the topics and people most likely to be selected by Nobel selection committee.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/clarivate-analytics] From 2002 to 2020, 59 individuals listed as Citation Laureates have received Nobel prizes.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/clarivate-analytics] The annual Top 100 Global Innovators report identifies the world's most innovative organizations.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/clarivate-analytics] These businesses have successfully developed valuable patented inventions that also have strong commercialization potential based on market reach and impact on other downstream inventions.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/clarivate-analytics] The 2020 Top 100 Global Innovators Report was released on February 19, 2020.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Natural forces cause some variability, but the persistent temperature increase shows the progressive influence of human activity.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Present-day **climate change** includes both **global warming**—the ongoing increase in global average temperature—and its wider effects on Earth's climate system.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Climate change in a broader sense also includes previous long-term changes to Earth's climate.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] The modern-day rise in global temperatures is driven by human activities, especially fossil fuel (coal, oil and natural gas) burning since the Industrial Revolution.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Fossil fuel use, deforestation, and some agricultural and industrial practices release greenhouse gases.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] These gases absorb some of the heat that the Earth radiates after it warms from sunlight, warming the lower atmosphere.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Earth's atmosphere now has roughly 50% more carbon dioxide, the main gas driving global warming, than it did at the end of the pre-industrial era, reaching levels not seen for millions of years.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Climate change has an increasingly large impact on the environment.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Heat waves and wildfires are becoming more common.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Amplified warming in the Arctic has contributed to thawing permafrost, retreat of glaciers and sea ice decline.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Higher temperatures are also causing more intense storms, droughts, and other weather extremes.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Rapid environmental change in mountains, coral reefs, and the Arctic is forcing many species to relocate or become extinct.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Even if efforts to minimize future warming are successful, some effects will continue for centuries.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] These include ocean heating, ocean acidification and sea level rise.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Climate change threatens people with increased flooding, extreme heat, increased food and water scarcity, more disease, and economic loss.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Human migration and conflict can also be a result.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] The World Health Organization calls climate change one of the biggest threats to global health in the 21st century.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Societies and ecosystems will experience more severe risks without action to limit warming.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Adapting to climate change through efforts like flood control measures or drought-resistant crops partially reduces climate change risks, although some limits to adaptation have already been reached.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Poorer communities are responsible for a small share of global emissions, yet have the least ability to adapt and are most vulnerable to climate change.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] , and worsening droughts compromising water supplies.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Many climate change impacts have been observed in the first decades of the 21st century, with 2024 the warmest on record at +1.60 °C (2.88 °F) since regular tracking began in 1850.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Additional warming will increase these impacts and can trigger tipping points, such as melting all of the Greenland ice sheet.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Under the 2015 Paris Agreement, nations collectively agreed to keep warming "well under 2 °C".
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] However, with pledges made under the Agreement, global warming would still reach about 2.8 °C (5.0 °F) by the end of the century.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] There is widespread support for climate action worldwide, and most countries aim to stop emitting carbon dioxide.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Fossil fuels can be phased out by ending their subsidies, conserving energy and switching to energy sources that do not produce significant carbon pollution.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] These energy sources include wind, solar, hydro, and nuclear power.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Cleanly generated electricity can replace fossil fuels for powering transportation, heating buildings, and running industrial processes.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Carbon can also be removed from the atmosphere, for instance by increasing forest cover and farming with methods that store carbon in soil.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Before the 1980s, it was unclear whether the warming effect of increased greenhouse gases was stronger than the cooling effect of airborne particulates in air pollution.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Scientists used the term *inadvertent climate modification* to refer to human impacts on the climate at this time.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] In the 1980s, the terms *global warming* and *climate change* became more common, often being used interchangeably.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Scientifically, *global warming* refers only to increased global average surface temperature, while *climate change* describes both global warming and its effects on Earth's climate system, such as precipitation changes.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Over the last few million years the climate cycled through ice ages.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] One of the hotter periods was the Last Interglacial, around 125,000 years ago, where temperatures were between 0.5 °C and 1.5 °C warmer than before the start of global warming.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] This period saw sea levels 5 to 10 metres higher than today.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] The most recent glacial maximum 20,000 years ago was some 5–7 °C colder.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] This period has sea levels that were over 125 metres (410 ft) lower than today.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Temperatures stabilized in the current interglacial period beginning 11,700 years ago.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] This period also saw the start of agriculture.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Historical patterns of warming and cooling, like the Medieval Warm Period and the Little Ice Age, did not occur at the same time across different regions.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Temperatures may have reached as high as those of the late 20th century in a limited set of regions.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Climate information for that period comes from climate proxies, such as trees and ice cores.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Around 1850 thermometer records began to provide global coverage.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Between the 18th century and 1970 there was little net warming, as the warming impact of greenhouse gas emissions was offset by cooling from sulfur dioxide emissions.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Sulfur dioxide causes acid rain, but it also produces sulfate aerosols in the atmosphere, which reflect sunlight and cause global dimming.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] After 1970, the increasing accumulation of greenhouse gases and controls on sulfur pollution led to a marked increase in temperature.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Ongoing changes in climate have had no precedent for several thousand years.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Multiple datasets all show worldwide increases in surface temperature, at a rate of around 0.2 °C per decade.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Not every single year was warmer than the last: internal climate variability processes can make any year 0.2 °C warmer or colder than the average.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] From 1998 to 2013, negative phases of two such processes, Pacific Decadal Oscillation (PDO) and Atlantic Multidecadal Oscillation (AMO) caused a short slower period of warming called the "global warming hiatus".
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] After the "hiatus", the opposite occurred, with 2024 well above the recent average at more than +1.5 °C.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] This is why the temperature change is defined in terms of a 20-year average, which reduces the noise of hot and cold years and decadal climate patterns, and detects the long-term signal.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] A wide range of other observations reinforce the evidence of warming.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] The upper atmosphere is cooling, because greenhouse gases are trapping heat near the Earth's surface, and so less heat is radiating into space.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Warming reduces average snow cover and forces the retreat of glaciers.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] At the same time, warming also causes greater evaporation from the oceans, leading to more atmospheric humidity, and more and heavier precipitation.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Plants are flowering earlier in spring, and thousands of animal species have been permanently moving to cooler areas.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Different regions of the world warm at different rates.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] The pattern is independent of where greenhouse gases are emitted, because the gases persist long enough to diffuse across the planet.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Since the pre-industrial period, the average surface temperature over land regions has increased almost twice as fast as the global average surface temperature.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] This is because oceans lose more heat by evaporation and oceans can store a lot of heat.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] The thermal energy in the global climate system has grown with only brief pauses since at least 1970, and over 90% of this extra energy has been stored in the ocean.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] The rest has heated the atmosphere, melted ice, and warmed the continents.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] The Northern Hemisphere and the North Pole have warmed much faster than the South Pole and Southern Hemisphere.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] The Northern Hemisphere not only has much more land, but also more seasonal snow cover and sea ice.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] As these surfaces flip from reflecting a lot of light to being dark after the ice has melted, they start absorbing more heat.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Local black carbon deposits on snow and ice also contribute to Arctic warming.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Arctic surface temperatures are increasing between three and four times faster than in the rest of the world.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Melting of ice sheets near the poles weakens both the Atlantic and the Antarctic limb of thermohaline circulation, which further changes the distribution of heat and precipitation around the globe.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] The World Meteorological Organization estimates there is almost a 50% chance of the five-year average global temperature exceeding +1.5 °C between 2024 and 2028.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] The IPCC expects the 20-year average to exceed +1.5 °C in the early 2030s.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] The IPCC Sixth Assessment Report (2021) included projections that by 2100 global warming is very likely to reach 1.0–1.8 °C under a scenario with very low emissions of greenhouse gases, 2.1–3.5 °C under an intermediate emissions scenario, or 3.3–5.7 °C under a very high emissions scenario.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] The warming will continue past 2100 in the intermediate and high emission scenarios, with future projections of global surface temperatures by year 2300 being similar to millions of years ago.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] The remaining carbon budget for staying beneath certain temperature increases is determined by modelling the carbon cycle and climate sensitivity to greenhouse gases.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] According to UNEP, global warming can be kept below 2.0 °C with a 50% chance if emissions after 2023 do not exceed 900 gigatonnes of CO2.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] This carbon budget corresponds to around 16 years of current emissions.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] The climate system experiences various cycles on its own which can last for years, decades or even centuries.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] For example, El Niño events cause short-term spikes in surface temperature while La Niña events cause short term cooling.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Their relative frequency can affect global temperature trends on a decadal timescale.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Other changes are caused by an imbalance of energy from external forcings.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Examples of these include changes in the concentrations of greenhouse gases, solar luminosity, volcanic eruptions, and variations in the Earth's orbit around the Sun.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] To determine the human contribution to climate change, unique "fingerprints" for all potential causes are developed and compared with both observed patterns and known internal climate variability.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] For example, solar forcing—whose fingerprint involves warming the entire atmosphere—is ruled out because only the lower atmosphere has warmed.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Atmospheric aerosols produce a smaller, cooling effect.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Other drivers, such as changes in albedo, are less impactful.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Greenhouse gases are transparent to sunlight, and thus allow it to pass through the atmosphere to heat the Earth's surface.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] The Earth radiates it as heat, and greenhouse gases absorb a portion of it.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] This absorption slows the rate at which heat escapes into space, trapping heat near the Earth's surface and warming it over time.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] While water vapour (≈50%) and clouds (≈25%) are the biggest contributors to the greenhouse effect, they primarily change as a function of temperature and are therefore mostly considered to be feedbacks that change climate sensitivity.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] On the other hand, concentrations of gases such as CO2 (≈20%), tropospheric ozone, CFCs and nitrous oxide are added or removed independently from temperature, and are therefore considered to be external forcings that change global temperatures.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Before the Industrial Revolution, naturally occurring amounts of greenhouse gases caused the air near the surface to be about 33 °C warmer than it would have been in their absence.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Human activity since the Industrial Revolution, mainly extracting and burning fossil fuels (coal, oil, and natural gas), has increased the amount of greenhouse gases in the atmosphere.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] In 2022, the concentrations of CO2 and methane had increased by about 50% and 164%, respectively, since 1750.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] These CO2 levels are higher than they have been at any time during the last 14 million years.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Concentrations of methane are far higher than they were over the last 800,000 years.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Global human-caused greenhouse gas emissions in 2019 were equivalent to 59 billion tonnes of CO2.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Of these emissions, 75% was CO2, 18% was methane, 4% was nitrous oxide, and 2% was fluorinated gases.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] CO2 emissions primarily come from burning fossil fuels to provide energy for transport, manufacturing, heating, and electricity.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Additional CO2 emissions come from deforestation and industrial processes, which include the CO2 released by the chemical reactions for making cement, steel, aluminium, and fertilizer.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Methane emissions come from livestock, manure, rice cultivation, landfills, wastewater, and coal mining, as well as oil and gas extraction.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Nitrous oxide emissions largely come from the microbial decomposition of fertilizer.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] While methane only lasts in the atmosphere for an average of 12 years, CO2 lasts much longer.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] The Earth's surface absorbs CO2 as part of the carbon cycle.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] While plants on land and in the ocean absorb most excess emissions of CO2 every year, that CO2 is returned to the atmosphere when biological matter is digested, burns, or decays.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Land-surface carbon sink processes, such as carbon fixation in the soil and photosynthesis, remove about 29% of annual global CO2 emissions.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] The ocean has absorbed 20 to 30% of emitted CO2 over the last two decades.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] CO2 is only removed from the atmosphere for the long term when it is stored in the Earth's crust, which is a process that can take millions of years to complete.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Around 30% of Earth's land area is largely unusable for humans (glaciers, deserts, etc.), 26% is forests, 10% is shrubland and 34% is agricultural land.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Deforestation is the main land use change contributor to global warming, as the destroyed trees release CO2, and are not replaced by new trees, removing that carbon sink.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Between 2001 and 2018, 27% of deforestation was from permanent clearing to enable agricultural expansion for crops and livestock.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Another 24% has been lost to temporary clearing under the shifting cultivation agricultural systems.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] 26% was due to logging for wood and derived products, and wildfires have accounted for the remaining 23%.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Some forests have not been fully cleared, but were already degraded by these impacts.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Restoring these forests also recovers their potential as a carbon sink.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Local vegetation cover impacts how much of the sunlight gets reflected back into space (albedo), and how much heat is lost by evaporation.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] For instance, the change from a dark forest to grassland makes the surface lighter, causing it to reflect more sunlight.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Deforestation can also modify the release of chemical compounds that influence clouds, and can change the roughness of Earth’s surface in a way affecting wind speed.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] In tropic and temperate areas the net effect is to produce significant warming, and forest restoration can make local temperatures cooler.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] At latitudes closer to the poles, there is a cooling effect as forest is replaced by snow-covered (and more reflective) plains.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Globally, these increases in surface albedo have been the dominant direct influence on temperature from land use change.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Thus, land use change to date is estimated to have a slight cooling effect.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Air pollution, in the form of aerosols, affects the climate on a large scale.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Aerosols scatter and absorb solar radiation.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] From 1961 to 1990, a gradual reduction in the amount of sunlight reaching the Earth's surface was observed.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] This phenomenon is popularly known as *global dimming*, and is primarily attributed to sulfate aerosols produced by the combustion of fossil fuels with heavy sulfur concentrations like coal and bunker fuel.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Smaller contributions come from black carbon (from combustion of fossil fuels and biomass), and from dust.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Globally, aerosols have been declining since 1990 due to pollution controls, meaning that they no longer mask greenhouse gas warming as much.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Aerosols also have indirect effects on the Earth's energy budget.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Sulfate aerosols act as cloud condensation nuclei and lead to clouds that have more and smaller cloud droplets.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] These clouds reflect solar radiation more efficiently than clouds with fewer and larger droplets.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] They also reduce the growth of raindrops, which makes clouds more reflective to incoming sunlight.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Indirect effects of aerosols are the largest uncertainty in radiative forcing.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] While aerosols typically limit global warming by reflecting sunlight, black carbon in soot that falls on snow or ice can contribute to global warming.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] The resulting excess heat accelerates the melting of ice sheets and glaciers, which in turn contributes significantly to global sea-level rise.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Limiting new black carbon deposits in the Arctic could reduce global warming by 0.2 °C by 2050.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] The effect of decreasing sulfur content of fuel oil for ships since 2020 is estimated to cause an additional 0.05 °C increase in global mean temperature by 2050.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] As the Sun is the Earth's primary energy source, changes in incoming sunlight directly affect the climate system.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Solar irradiance has been measured directly by satellites, and indirect measurements are available from the early 1600s onwards.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Since 1880, there has been no upward trend in the amount of the Sun's energy reaching the Earth, in contrast to the warming of the lower atmosphere (the troposphere).
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] The upper atmosphere (the stratosphere) would also be warming if the Sun was sending more energy to Earth, but instead, it has been cooling.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] This is consistent with greenhouse gases preventing heat from leaving the Earth's atmosphere.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Explosive volcanic eruptions can release gases, dust and ash that partially block sunlight and reduce temperatures, or they can send water vapour into the atmosphere, which adds to greenhouse gases and increases temperatures.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] These impacts on temperature only last for several years, because both water vapour and volcanic material have low persistence in the atmosphere.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Volcanic CO2 emissions are more persistent, but they are equivalent to less than 1% of current human-caused CO2 emissions.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Volcanic activity still represents the single largest natural impact (forcing) on temperature in the industrial era.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Yet, like the other natural forcings, it has had negligible impacts on global temperature trends since the Industrial Revolution.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] The climate system's response to an initial forcing is shaped by feedbacks, which either amplify or dampen the change.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] *Self-reinforcing* or *positive* feedbacks increase the response, while *balancing* or *negative* feedbacks reduce it.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] The main reinforcing feedbacks are the water-vapour feedback, the ice–albedo feedback, and the net cloud feedback.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] The primary balancing mechanism is radiative cooling, as Earth's surface gives off more heat to space in response to rising temperature.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] In addition to temperature feedbacks, there are feedbacks in the carbon cycle, such as the fertilizing effect of CO2 on plant growth.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Feedbacks are expected to trend in a positive direction as greenhouse gas emissions continue, raising climate sensitivity.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] These feedback processes alter the pace of global warming.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] For instance, warmer air can hold more moisture in the form of water vapour, which is itself a potent greenhouse gas.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Warmer air can also make clouds higher and thinner, and therefore more insulating, increasing climate warming.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] The reduction of snow cover and sea ice in the Arctic is another major feedback, this reduces the reflectivity of the Earth's surface in the region and accelerates Arctic warming.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] This additional warming also contributes to permafrost thawing, which releases methane and CO2 into the atmosphere.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Around half of human-caused CO2 emissions have been absorbed by land plants and by the oceans.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] This fraction is not static and if future CO2 emissions decrease, the Earth will be able to absorb up to around 70%.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] If they increase substantially, it'll still absorb more carbon than now, but the overall fraction will decrease to below 40%.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] This is because climate change increases droughts and heat waves that eventually inhibit plant growth on land, and soils will release more carbon from dead plants when they are warmer.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] The rate at which oceans absorb atmospheric carbon will be lowered as they become more acidic and experience changes in thermohaline circulation and phytoplankton distribution.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Uncertainty over feedbacks, particularly cloud cover, is the major reason why different climate models project different magnitudes of warming for a given amount of emissions.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] A climate model is a representation of the physical, chemical and biological processes that affect the climate system.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Models include natural processes like changes in the Earth's orbit, historical changes in the Sun's activity, and volcanic forcing.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Models are used to estimate the degree of warming future emissions will cause when accounting for the strength of climate feedbacks.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Models also predict the circulation of the oceans, the annual cycle of the seasons, and the flows of carbon between the land surface and the atmosphere.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] The physical realism of models is tested by examining their ability to simulate current or past climates.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Past models have underestimated the rate of Arctic shrinkage and underestimated the rate of precipitation increase.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Sea level rise since 1990 was underestimated in older models, but more recent models agree well with observations.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] The 2017 United States-published National Climate Assessment notes that "climate models may still be underestimating or missing relevant feedback processes".
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Additionally, climate models may be unable to adequately predict short-term regional climatic shifts.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] A subset of climate models add societal factors to a physical climate model.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] These models simulate how population, economic growth, and energy use affect—and interact with—the physical climate.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] With this information, these models can produce scenarios of future greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] This is then used as input for physical climate models and carbon cycle models to predict how atmospheric concentrations of greenhouse gases might change.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Depending on the socioeconomic scenario and the mitigation scenario, models produce atmospheric CO2 concentrations that range widely between 380 and 1400 ppm.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] The environmental effects of climate change are broad and far-reaching, affecting oceans, ice, and weather.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Evidence for these effects comes from studying climate change in the past, from modelling, and from modern observations.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Since the 1950s, droughts and heat waves have appeared simultaneously with increasing frequency.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Extremely wet or dry events within the monsoon period have increased in India and East Asia.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Monsoonal precipitation over the Northern Hemisphere has increased since 1980.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] The rainfall rate and intensity of hurricanes and typhoons is likely increasing, and the geographic range likely expanding poleward in response to climate warming.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] The frequency of tropical cyclones has not increased as a result of climate change.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Global sea level is rising as a consequence of thermal expansion and the melting of glaciers and ice sheets.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Sea level rise has increased over time, reaching 4.8 cm per decade between 2014 and 2023.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Over the 21st century, the IPCC projects 32–62 cm of sea level rise under a low emission scenario, 44–76 cm under an intermediate one and 65–101 cm under a very high emission scenario.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Marine ice sheet instability processes in Antarctica may add substantially to these values, including the possibility of a 2-meter sea level rise by 2100 under high emissions.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Climate change has led to decades of shrinking and thinning of the Arctic sea ice.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] While ice-free summers are expected to be rare at 1.5 °C degrees of warming, they are set to occur once every three to ten years at a warming level of 2 °C.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Higher atmospheric CO2 concentrations cause more CO2 to dissolve in the oceans, which is making them more acidic.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Because oxygen is less soluble in warmer water, its concentrations in the ocean are decreasing, and dead zones are expanding.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Greater degrees of global warming increase the risk of passing through 'tipping points'—thresholds beyond which certain major impacts can no longer be avoided even if temperatures return to their previous state.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] For instance, the Greenland ice sheet is already melting, but if global warming reaches levels between 1.7 °C and 2.3 °C, its melting will continue until it fully disappears.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] If the warming is later reduced to 1.5 °C or less, it will still lose a lot more ice than if the warming was never allowed to reach the threshold in the first place.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] While the ice sheets would melt over millennia, other tipping points would occur faster and give societies less time to respond.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] The collapse of major ocean currents like the Atlantic meridional overturning circulation (AMOC), and irreversible damage to key ecosystems like the Amazon rainforest and coral reefs can unfold in a matter of decades.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] The collapse of the AMOC would be a severe climate catastrophe, resulting in a cooling of the Northern Hemisphere.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] The long-term effects of climate change on oceans include further ice melt, ocean warming, sea level rise, ocean acidification and ocean deoxygenation.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] The timescale of long-term impacts are centuries to millennia due to CO2's long atmospheric lifetime.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] The result is an estimated total sea level rise of 2.3 metres per degree Celsius (4.2 ft/°F) after 2000 years.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Oceanic CO2 uptake is slow enough that ocean acidification will also continue for hundreds to thousands of years.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Deep oceans (below 2,000 metres (6,600 ft)) are also already committed to losing over 10% of their dissolved oxygen by the warming which occurred to date.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Further, the West Antarctic ice sheet appears committed to practically irreversible melting, which would increase the sea levels by at least 3.3 m (10 ft 10 in) over approximately 2000 years.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Recent warming has driven many terrestrial and freshwater species poleward and towards higher altitudes.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] For instance, the range of hundreds of North American birds has shifted northward at an average rate of 1.5 km/year over the past 55 years.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Higher atmospheric CO2 levels and an extended growing season have resulted in global greening.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] However, heatwaves and drought have reduced ecosystem productivity in some regions.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] The future balance of these opposing effects is unclear.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] A related phenomenon driven by climate change is woody plant encroachment, affecting up to 500 million hectares globally.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Climate change has contributed to the expansion of drier climate zones, such as the expansion of deserts in the subtropics.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] The size and speed of global warming is making abrupt changes in ecosystems more likely.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Overall, it is expected that climate change will result in the extinction of many species.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] The oceans have heated more slowly than the land, but plants and animals in the ocean have migrated towards the colder poles faster than species on land.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Just as on land, heat waves in the ocean occur more frequently due to climate change, harming a wide range of organisms such as corals, kelp, and seabirds.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Ocean acidification makes it harder for marine calcifying organisms such as mussels, barnacles and corals to produce shells and skeletons; and heatwaves have bleached coral reefs.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Harmful algal blooms enhanced by climate change and eutrophication lower oxygen levels, disrupt food webs and cause great loss of marine life.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Coastal ecosystems are under particular stress.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Almost half of global wetlands have disappeared due to climate change and other human impacts.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Plants have come under increased stress from damage by insects.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] The effects of climate change are impacting humans everywhere in the world.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Impacts can be observed on all continents and ocean regions, with low-latitude, less developed areas facing the greatest risk.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Continued warming has potentially "severe, pervasive and irreversible impacts" for people and ecosystems.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] The risks are unevenly distributed, but are generally greater for disadvantaged people in developing and developed countries.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Scientists have warned about the irreversible harms it poses.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Extreme weather events affect public health, and food and water security.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Temperature extremes lead to increased illness and death.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Climate change increases the intensity and frequency of extreme weather events.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] It can affect transmission of infectious diseases, such as dengue fever and malaria.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] According to the World Economic Forum, 14.5 million more deaths are expected due to climate change by 2050.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] 30% of the global population currently live in areas where extreme heat and humidity are already associated with excess deaths.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] By 2100, 50% to 75% of the global population would live in such areas.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] While total crop yields have been increasing in the past 50 years due to agricultural improvements, climate change has already decreased the rate of yield growth.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Fisheries have been negatively affected in multiple regions.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] While agricultural productivity has been positively affected in some high latitude areas, mid- and low-latitude areas have been negatively affected.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Climate change affects land suitability for many crops, with suitable areas for given crops usually moving to higher latitudes and altitudes.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] According to the World Economic Forum, an increase in drought in certain regions could cause 3.2 million deaths from malnutrition by 2050 and stunting in children.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] With 2 °C warming, global livestock headcounts could decline by 7–10% by 2050, as less animal feed will be available.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] If the emissions continue to increase for the rest of century, then over 9 million climate-related deaths would occur annually by 2100.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Economic damages due to climate change may be severe and there is a chance of disastrous consequences.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Severe impacts are expected in South-East Asia and sub-Saharan Africa, where most of the local inhabitants are dependent upon natural and agricultural resources.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Heat stress can prevent outdoor labourers from working.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] If warming reaches 4 °C then labour capacity in those regions could be reduced by 30 to 50%.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] The World Bank estimates that between 2016 and 2030, climate change could drive over 120 million people into extreme poverty without adaptation.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Inequalities based on wealth and social status have worsened due to climate change.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Major difficulties in mitigating, adapting to, and recovering from climate shocks are faced by marginalized people who have less control over resources.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Indigenous people, who are subsistent on their land and ecosystems, will face endangerment to their wellness and lifestyles due to climate change.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] An expert elicitation concluded that the role of climate change in armed conflict has been small compared to factors such as socio-economic inequality and state capabilities.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] While women are not inherently more at risk from climate change and shocks, limits on women's resources and discriminatory gender norms constrain their adaptive capacity and resilience.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] For example, women's work burdens, including hours worked in agriculture, tend to decline less than men's during climate shocks such as heat stress.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Climate change threatens the sports economy by disrupting seasons, damaging infrastructure and reducing fan engagement, with the most immediate risks seen in football, winter sports and outdoor events.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Low-lying islands and coastal communities are threatened by sea level rise, which makes urban flooding more common.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Sometimes, land is permanently lost to the sea.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] This could lead to statelessness for people in island nations, such as the Maldives and Tuvalu.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] In some regions, the rise in temperature and humidity may be too severe for humans to adapt to.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] With worst-case climate change, models project that areas almost one-third of humanity live in might become Sahara-like uninhabitable and extremely hot climates.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] These factors can drive climate or environmental migration, within and between countries.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] More people are expected to be displaced because of sea level rise, extreme weather and conflict from increased competition over natural resources.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Climate change may also increase vulnerability, leading to "trapped populations" who are not able to move due to a lack of resources.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Climate change can be mitigated by reducing the rate at which greenhouse gases are emitted into the atmosphere, and by increasing the rate at which carbon dioxide is removed from the atmosphere.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] To limit global warming to less than 2 °C global greenhouse gas emissions need to be net-zero by 2070.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] This requires far-reaching, systemic changes on an unprecedented scale in energy, land, cities, transport, buildings, and industry.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] The United Nations Environment Programme estimates that countries need to triple their pledges under the Paris Agreement within the next decade to limit global warming to 2 °C.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] With pledges made under the Paris Agreement as of 2024, there would be a 66% chance that global warming is kept under 2.8 °C by the end of the century (range: 1.9–3.7 °C, depending on exact implementation and technological progress).
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] When only considering current policies, this raises to 3.1 °C.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Globally, limiting warming to 2 °C may result in higher economic benefits than economic costs.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Although there is no single pathway to limit global warming to 2 °C, most scenarios and strategies see a major increase in the use of renewable energy in combination with increased energy efficiency measures to generate the needed greenhouse gas reductions.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] To reduce pressures on ecosystems and enhance their carbon sequestration capabilities, changes would also be necessary in agriculture and forestry, such as preventing deforestation and restoring natural ecosystems by reforestation.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Other approaches to mitigating climate change have a higher level of risk.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Scenarios that limit global warming to 1.5 °C typically project the large-scale use of carbon dioxide removal methods over the 21st century.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] There are concerns, though, about over-reliance on these technologies, and environmental impacts.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Solar radiation modification (SRM) is a proposal for reducing global warming by reflecting some sunlight away from Earth and back into space.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Because it does not reduce greenhouse gas concentrations, it would not address ocean acidification and is not considered mitigation.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] SRM should be considered only as a supplement to mitigation, not a replacement for it, due to risks such as rapid warming if it were abruptly stopped and not restarted.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] The most-studied approach is stratospheric aerosol injection.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] SRM could reduce global warming and some of its impacts, though imperfectly.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] It poses environmental risks, such as changes to rainfall patterns, as well as political challenges, such as who would decide whether to use it.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Renewable energy is key to limiting climate change.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] For decades, fossil fuels have accounted for roughly 80% of the world's energy use.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] The remaining share has been split between nuclear power and renewables (including hydropower, bioenergy, wind and solar power and geothermal energy).
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Fossil fuel use is expected to peak in absolute terms prior to 2030 and then to decline, with coal use experiencing the sharpest reductions.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Renewables represented 86% of all new electricity generation installed in 2023.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Other forms of clean energy, such as nuclear and hydropower, currently have a larger share of the energy supply.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] However, their future growth forecasts appear limited in comparison.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] While solar panels and onshore wind are now among the cheapest forms of adding new power generation capacity in many locations, green energy policies are needed to achieve a rapid transition from fossil fuels to renewables.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] To achieve carbon neutrality by 2050, renewable energy would become the dominant form of electricity generation, rising to 85% or more by 2050 in some scenarios.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Investment in coal would be eliminated and coal use nearly phased out by 2050.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Electricity generated from renewable sources would also need to become the main energy source for heating and transport.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Transport can switch away from internal combustion engine vehicles and towards electric vehicles, public transit, and active transport (cycling and walking).
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] For shipping and flying, low-carbon fuels would reduce emissions.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Heating could be increasingly decarbonized with technologies like heat pumps.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] There are obstacles to the continued rapid growth of clean energy, including renewables.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Wind and solar produce energy intermittently and with seasonal variability.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Traditionally, hydro dams with reservoirs and fossil fuel power plants have been used when variable energy production is low.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Going forward, battery storage can be expanded, energy demand and supply can be matched, and long-distance transmission can smooth variability of renewable outputs.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Bioenergy is often not carbon-neutral and may have negative consequences for food security.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] The growth of nuclear power is constrained by controversy around radioactive waste, nuclear weapon proliferation, and accidents.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Hydropower growth is limited by the fact that the best sites have been developed, and new projects are confronting increased social and environmental concerns.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Low-carbon energy improves human health by minimizing climate change as well as reducing air pollution deaths, which were estimated at 7 million annually in 2016.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Meeting the Paris Agreement goals that limit warming to a 2 °C increase could save about a million of those lives per year by 2050, whereas limiting global warming to 1.5 °C could save millions and simultaneously increase energy security and reduce poverty.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Improving air quality also has economic benefits which may be larger than mitigation costs.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Reducing energy demand is another major aspect of reducing emissions.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] If less energy is needed, there is more flexibility for clean energy development.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] It also makes it easier to manage the electricity grid, and minimizes carbon-intensive infrastructure development.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Major increases in energy efficiency investment will be required to achieve climate goals, comparable to the level of investment in renewable energy.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Several COVID-19 related changes in energy use patterns, energy efficiency investments, and funding have made forecasts for this decade more difficult and uncertain.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Strategies to reduce energy demand vary by sector.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] In the transport sector, passengers and freight can switch to more efficient travel modes, such as buses and trains, or use electric vehicles.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Industrial strategies to reduce energy demand include improving heating systems and motors, designing less energy-intensive products, and increasing product lifetimes.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] In the building sector the focus is on better design of new buildings, and higher levels of energy efficiency in retrofitting.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] The use of technologies like heat pumps can also increase building energy efficiency.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Agriculture and forestry face a triple challenge of limiting greenhouse gas emissions, preventing the further conversion of forests to agricultural land, and meeting increases in world food demand.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] A set of actions could reduce agriculture and forestry-based emissions by two-thirds from 2010 levels.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] These include reducing growth in demand for food and other agricultural products, increasing land productivity, protecting and restoring forests, and reducing greenhouse gas emissions from agricultural production.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] On the demand side, a key component of reducing emissions is shifting people towards plant-based diets.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Eliminating the production of livestock for meat and dairy would eliminate about three-quarters of all emissions from agriculture and other land use.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Livestock also occupy 37% of ice-free land area on Earth and consume feed from the 12% of land area used for crops, driving deforestation and land degradation.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Steel and cement production are responsible for about 13% of industrial CO2 emissions.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] In these industries, carbon-intensive materials such as coke and lime play an integral role in the production, so that reducing CO2 emissions requires research into alternative chemistries.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Where energy production or CO2-intensive heavy industries continue to produce waste CO2, technology can sometimes be used to capture and store most of the gas instead of releasing it to the atmosphere.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] This technology, carbon capture and storage (CCS), could have a critical but limited role in reducing emissions.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] It is relatively expensive and has been deployed only to an extent that removes around 0.1% of annual greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Natural carbon sinks can be enhanced to sequester significantly larger amounts of CO2 beyond naturally occurring levels.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Reforestation and afforestation (planting forests where there were none before) are among the most mature sequestration techniques, although the latter raises food security concerns.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Farmers can promote sequestration of carbon in soils through practices such as use of winter cover crops, reducing the intensity and frequency of tillage, and using compost and manure as soil amendments.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Forest and landscape restoration yields many benefits for the climate, including greenhouse gas emissions sequestration and reduction.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Restoration/recreation of coastal wetlands, prairie plots and seagrass meadows increases the uptake of carbon into organic matter.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] When carbon is sequestered in soils and in organic matter such as trees, there is a risk of the carbon being re-released into the atmosphere later through changes in land use, fire, or other changes in ecosystems.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] The use of bioenergy in conjunction with carbon capture and storage (BECCS) can result in net negative emissions as CO2 is drawn from the atmosphere.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] It remains highly uncertain whether carbon dioxide removal techniques will be able to play a large role in limiting warming to 1.5 °C.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p01] Policy decisions that rely on carbon dioxide removal increase the risk of global warming rising beyond international goals.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] Adaptation is "the process of adjustment to current or expected changes in climate and its effects".
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] Without additional mitigation, adaptation cannot avert the risk of "severe, widespread and irreversible" impacts.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] More severe climate change requires more transformative adaptation, which can be prohibitively expensive.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] The capacity and potential for humans to adapt is unevenly distributed across different regions and populations, and developing countries generally have less.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] The first two decades of the 21st century saw an increase in adaptive capacity in most low- and middle-income countries with improved access to basic sanitation and electricity, but progress is slow.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] Many countries have implemented adaptation policies.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] However, there is a considerable gap between necessary and available finance.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] Adaptation to sea level rise consists of avoiding at-risk areas, learning to live with increased flooding, and building flood controls.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] If that fails, managed retreat may be needed.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] There are economic barriers for tackling dangerous heat impact.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] Avoiding strenuous work or having air conditioning is not possible for everybody.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] In agriculture, adaptation options include a switch to more sustainable diets, diversification, erosion control, and genetic improvements for increased tolerance to a changing climate.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] Insurance allows for risk-sharing, but is often difficult to get for people on lower incomes.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] Education, migration and early warning systems can reduce climate vulnerability.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] Planting mangroves or encouraging other coastal vegetation can buffer storms.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] Ecosystems adapt to climate change, a process that can be supported by human intervention.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] By increasing connectivity between ecosystems, species can migrate to more favourable climate conditions.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] Species can also be introduced to areas acquiring a favourable climate.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] Protection and restoration of natural and semi-natural areas helps build resilience, making it easier for ecosystems to adapt.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] Many of the actions that promote adaptation in ecosystems, also help humans adapt via ecosystem-based adaptation.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] For instance, restoration of natural fire regimes makes catastrophic fires less likely, and reduces human exposure.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] Giving rivers more space allows for more water storage in the natural system, reducing flood risk.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] Restored forest acts as a carbon sink, but planting trees in unsuitable regions can exacerbate climate impacts.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] There are synergies but also trade-offs between adaptation and mitigation.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] An example for synergy is increased food productivity, which has large benefits for both adaptation and mitigation.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] An example of a trade-off is that increased use of air conditioning allows people to better cope with heat, but increases energy demand.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] Another trade-off example is that more compact urban development may reduce emissions from transport and construction, but may also increase the urban heat island effect, exposing people to heat-related health risks.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] ranks countries by greenhouse gas emissions (40% of score), renewable energy (20%), energy use (20%), and climate policy (20%).
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] Countries that are most vulnerable to climate change have typically been responsible for a small share of global emissions.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] This raises questions about justice and fairness.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] Limiting global warming makes it much easier to achieve the UN's Sustainable Development Goals, such as eradicating poverty and reducing inequalities.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] The connection is recognized in Sustainable Development Goal 13 which is to "take urgent action to combat climate change and its impacts".
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] The goals on food, clean water and ecosystem protection have synergies with climate mitigation.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] The geopolitics of climate change is complex.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] It has often been framed as a free-rider problem, in which all countries benefit from mitigation done by other countries, but individual countries would lose from switching to a low-carbon economy themselves.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] Sometimes mitigation also has localized benefits though.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] For instance, the benefits of a coal phase-out to public health and local environments exceed the costs in almost all regions.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] Furthermore, net importers of fossil fuels win economically from switching to clean energy, causing net exporters to face stranded assets: fossil fuels they cannot sell.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] A wide range of policies, regulations, and laws are being used to reduce emissions.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] As of 2019, carbon pricing covers about 20% of global greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] Carbon can be priced with carbon taxes and emissions trading systems.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] Direct global fossil fuel subsidies reached $319 billion in 2017, and $5.2 trillion when indirect costs such as air pollution are priced in.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] Ending these can cause a 28% reduction in global carbon emissions and a 46% reduction in air pollution deaths.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] Money saved on fossil subsidies could be used to support the transition to clean energy instead.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] More direct methods to reduce greenhouse gases include vehicle efficiency standards, renewable fuel standards, and air pollution regulations on heavy industry.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] Several countries require utilities to increase the share of renewables in power production.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] An Open Coalition on Compliance Carbon Markets with the aim of creating a global cap and trade system was established at COP30 (2025).
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] According to some calculations it can increase emissions reduction seven-fold over current policies, deliver $200 billion per year for clean-energy and social programs and even close the gap between current emissions trajectory and the goals of the Paris agreement.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] Policy designed through the lens of climate justice tries to address human rights issues and social inequality.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] According to proponents of climate justice, the costs of climate adaptation should be paid by those most responsible for climate change, while the beneficiaries of payments should be those suffering impacts.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] One way this can be addressed in practice is to have wealthy nations pay poorer countries to adapt.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] Oxfam found that in 2023 the wealthiest 10% of people were responsible for 50% of global emissions, while the bottom 50% were responsible for just 8%.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] Production of emissions is another way to look at responsibility: under that approach, the top 21 fossil fuel companies would owe cumulative climate reparations of $5.4 trillion over the period 2025–2050.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] To achieve a just transition, people working in the fossil fuel sector would also need other jobs, and their communities would need investments.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] Nearly all countries in the world are parties to the 1994 United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change (UNFCCC).
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] The goal of the UNFCCC is to prevent dangerous human interference with the climate system.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] As stated in the convention, this requires that greenhouse gas concentrations are stabilized in the atmosphere at a level where ecosystems can adapt naturally to climate change, food production is not threatened, and economic development can be sustained.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] The UNFCCC does not itself restrict emissions but rather provides a framework for protocols that do.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] Global emissions have risen since the UNFCCC was signed.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] Its yearly conferences are the stage of global negotiations.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] The 1997 Kyoto Protocol extended the UNFCCC and included legally binding commitments for most developed countries to limit their emissions.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] During the negotiations, the G77 (representing developing countries) pushed for a mandate requiring developed countries to "[take] the lead" in reducing their emissions, since developed countries contributed most to the accumulation of greenhouse gases in the atmosphere.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] Per-capita emissions were also still relatively low in developing countries and developing countries would need to emit more to meet their development needs.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] The 2009 Copenhagen Accord has been widely portrayed as disappointing because of its low goals, and was rejected by poorer nations including the G77.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] Associated parties aimed to limit the global temperature rise to below 2 °C.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] The accord set the goal of sending $100 billion per year to developing countries for mitigation and adaptation by 2020, and proposed the founding of the Green Climate Fund.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] As of 2020, only $83.3 billion were delivered.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] Only in 2023 the target is expected to be achieved.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] In 2015 all UN countries negotiated the Paris Agreement, which aims to keep global warming well below 2.0 °C and contains an aspirational goal of keeping warming under 1.5 °C.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] The agreement replaced the Kyoto Protocol.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] Unlike Kyoto, no binding emission targets were set in the Paris Agreement.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] Instead, a set of procedures was made binding.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] Countries have to regularly set ever more ambitious goals and reevaluate these goals every five years.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] The Paris Agreement restated that developing countries must be financially supported.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] As of March 2025, 194 states and the European Union have acceded to or ratified the agreement.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] The 1987 Montreal Protocol, an international agreement to phase out production of ozone-depleting gases, has had benefits for climate change mitigation.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] Several ozone-depleting gases like chlorofluorocarbons are powerful greenhouse gases, so banning their production and usage may have avoided a temperature rise of 0.5 °C–1.0 °C, as well as additional warming by preventing damage to vegetation from ultraviolet radiation.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] It is estimated that the agreement has been more effective at curbing greenhouse gas emissions than the Kyoto Protocol specifically designed to do so.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] The most recent amendment to the Montreal Protocol, the 2016 Kigali Amendment, committed to reducing the emissions of hydrofluorocarbons, which served as a replacement for banned ozone-depleting gases and are also potent greenhouse gases.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] Should countries comply with the amendment, a warming of 0.3 °C–0.5 °C is estimated to be avoided.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] In 2019, the United Kingdom parliament became the first national government to declare a climate emergency.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] Other countries and jurisdictions followed suit.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] That same year, the European Parliament declared a "climate and environmental emergency".
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] The European Commission presented its European Green Deal with the goal of making the EU carbon-neutral by 2050.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] In 2021, the European Commission released its "Fit for 55" legislation package, which contains guidelines for the car industry; all new cars on the European market must be zero-emission vehicles from 2035.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] Major countries in Asia have made similar pledges: South Korea and Japan have committed to become carbon-neutral by 2050, and China by 2060.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] While India has strong incentives for renewables, it also plans a significant expansion of coal in the country.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] Vietnam is among very few coal-dependent, fast-developing countries that pledged to phase out unabated coal power by the 2040s or as soon as possible thereafter.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] Public debate about climate change has been strongly affected by climate change denial and misinformation, which first emerged in the United States and has since spread to other countries, particularly Canada and Australia.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] It originated from fossil fuel companies, industry groups, conservative think tanks, and contrarian scientists.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] Like the tobacco industry, the main strategy of these groups has been to manufacture doubt about climate-change related scientific data and results.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] People who hold unwarranted doubt about climate change are sometimes called climate change "skeptics", although "contrarians" or "deniers" are more appropriate terms.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] There are different variants of climate denial: some deny that warming takes place at all, some acknowledge warming but attribute it to natural influences, and some minimize the negative impacts of climate change.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] Manufacturing uncertainty about the science later developed into a manufactured controversy: creating the belief that there is significant uncertainty about climate change within the scientific community to delay policy changes.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] Strategies to promote these ideas include criticism of scientific institutions, and questioning the motives of individual scientists.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] An echo chamber of climate-denying blogs and media has further fomented misunderstanding of climate change.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] Climate change came to international public attention in the late 1980s.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] Due to media coverage in the early 1990s, people often confused climate change with other environmental issues like ozone depletion.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] In popular culture, the climate fiction movie *The Day After Tomorrow* (2004) and the Al Gore documentary *An Inconvenient Truth* (2006) focused on climate change.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] Significant regional, gender, age and political differences exist in both public concern for, and understanding of, climate change.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] More highly educated people, and in some countries, women and younger people, were more likely to see climate change as a serious threat.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] College biology textbooks from the 2010s featured less content on climate change compared to those from the preceding decade, with decreasing emphasis on solutions.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] Partisan gaps also exist in many countries, and countries with high CO2 emissions tend to be less concerned.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] Views on causes of climate change vary widely between countries.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] Media coverage linked to protests has had impacts on public sentiment as well as on which aspects of climate change are focused upon.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] Higher levels of worry are associated with stronger public support for policies that address climate change.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] Concern has increased over time, and in 2021 a majority of citizens in 30 countries expressed a high level of worry about climate change, or view it as a global emergency.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] A 2024 survey across 125 countries found that 89% of the global population demanded intensified political action, but systematically underestimated other peoples' willingness to act.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] Climate protests demand that political leaders take action to prevent climate change.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] They can take the form of public demonstrations, fossil fuel divestment, lawsuits and other activities.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] Prominent demonstrations include the School Strike for Climate.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] In this initiative, young people across the globe have been protesting since 2018 by skipping school on Fridays, inspired by Swedish activist and then-teenager Greta Thunberg.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] Mass civil disobedience actions by groups like Extinction Rebellion have protested by disrupting roads and public transport.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] Litigation is increasingly used as a tool to strengthen climate action from public institutions and companies.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] Activists also initiate lawsuits which target governments and demand that they take ambitious action or enforce existing laws on climate change.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] Lawsuits against fossil-fuel companies generally seek compensation for loss and damage.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] On 23 July 2025, the UN's International Court of Justice issued its advisory opinion, saying explicitly that states must act to stop climate change, and if they fail to accomplish that duty, other states can sue them.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] This obligation includes implementing their commitments in international agreements they are parties to, such as the 2015 Paris Climate Accord.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] Scientists in the 19th century such as Alexander von Humboldt began to foresee the effects of climate change.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] In the 1820s, Joseph Fourier proposed the greenhouse effect to explain why Earth's temperature was higher than the Sun's energy alone could explain.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] Earth's atmosphere is transparent to sunlight, so sunlight reaches the surface where it is converted to heat.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] However, the atmosphere is not transparent to heat radiating from the surface, and captures some of that heat, which in turn warms the planet.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] In 1856 Eunice Newton Foote demonstrated that the warming effect of the Sun is greater for air with water vapour than for dry air, and that the effect is even greater with carbon dioxide (CO2).
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] In "Circumstances Affecting the Heat of the Sun's Rays" she concluded that "[a]n atmosphere of that gas would give to our earth a high temperature".
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] Starting in 1859, John Tyndall established that nitrogen and oxygen—together totalling 99% of dry air—are transparent to radiated heat.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] However, water vapour and gases such as methane and carbon dioxide absorb radiated heat and re-radiate that heat into the atmosphere.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] Tyndall proposed that changes in the concentrations of these gases may have caused climatic changes in the past, including ice ages.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] Svante Arrhenius noted that water vapour in air continuously varied, but the CO2 concentration in air was influenced by long-term geological processes.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] Warming from increased CO2 levels would increase the amount of water vapour, amplifying warming in a positive feedback loop.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] In 1896, he published the first climate model of its kind, projecting that halving CO2 levels could have produced a drop in temperature initiating an ice age.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] Arrhenius calculated the temperature increase expected from doubling CO2 to be around 5–6 °C.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] Other scientists were initially sceptical and believed that the greenhouse effect was saturated so that adding more CO2 would make no difference, and that the climate would be self-regulating.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] Beginning in 1938, Guy Stewart Callendar published evidence that climate was warming and CO2 levels were rising, but his calculations met the same objections.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] In the 1950s, Gilbert Plass created a detailed computer model that included different atmospheric layers and the infrared spectrum.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] This model predicted that increasing CO2 levels would cause warming.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] Around the same time, Hans Suess found evidence that CO2 levels had been rising, and Roger Revelle showed that the oceans would not absorb the increase.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] The two scientists subsequently helped Charles Keeling to begin a record of continued increase—the "Keeling Curve"—which was part of continued scientific investigation through the 1960s into possible human causation of global warming.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] Studies such as the National Research Council's 1979 Charney Report supported the accuracy of climate models that forecast significant warming.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] Human causation of observed global warming and dangers of unmitigated warming were publicly presented in James Hansen's 1988 testimony before a US Senate committee.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] The Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC), set up in 1988 to provide formal advice to the world's governments, spurred interdisciplinary research.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] As part of the IPCC reports, scientists assess the scientific discussion that takes place in peer-reviewed journal articles.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] There is a nearly unanimous scientific consensus that the climate is warming and that this is caused by human activities.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] No scientific body of national or international standing disagrees with this view.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] As of 2019, agreement in recent literature reached over 99%.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] The 2021 IPCC Assessment Report stated that it is "unequivocal" that climate change is caused by humans.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] Consensus has further developed that action should be taken to protect people against the impacts of climate change.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] National science academies have called on world leaders to cut global emissions.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] Extreme event attribution (EEA), also known as attribution science, was developed in the early decades of the 21st century.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] EEA uses climate models to identify and quantify the role that human-caused climate change plays in the frequency, intensity, duration, and impacts of specific individual extreme weather events.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] Greater computing power in the 2000s and conceptual breakthroughs in the early to mid 2010s enabled attribution science to detect the effects of climate change on some events with high confidence.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/climate-change-p02] Scientists use attribution methods and climate simulations that have already been peer reviewed, allowing "rapid attribution studies" to be published within a "news cycle" time frame after weather events.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/coastal-engineering] The areas of interest in coastal engineering include the coasts of the oceans, seas, marginal seas, estuaries and big lakes.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/coastal-engineering] Besides the design, building and maintenance of **coastal structures**, coastal engineers are often interdisciplinary involved in integrated coastal zone management, also because of their specific knowledge of the hydro- and morphodynamics of the coastal system.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/coastal-engineering] This may include providing input and technology for e.g. environmental impact assessment, port development, strategies for coastal defense, land reclamation, offshore wind farms and other energy-production facilities, etc.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/coastal-engineering] The History of coastal engineering can be dated back to the Early first century with the development of ancient ports in Rome such as the ports of Ostia and Portus.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/coastal-engineering] Evidence from carbon dating in archeological digs exhibit common properties of human efforts to form or change the two sites for the harbors.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/coastal-engineering] This was done by analyzing the radiocarbon content found in the different sediments.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/coastal-engineering] The group was able to analyze the sediment to approximate the different dredging phases that had been done.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/coastal-engineering] Particularly it seemed evident that there was planning for the quays and canals that were present in these two ports as well as many different dredging efforts in different phases.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/coastal-engineering] While the specific date can not be pinpointed, such structures that reflect modern breakwaters and harbor infrastructure were discovered in Greece by Pausinias, an ancient Greek geographer, in 122 AD in the town of Aegina along the Saronic Gulf.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/coastal-engineering] These structures were used as protection as well as controlled passages as entry into the ancient port.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/coastal-engineering] The new port in Aegina has been built on top of the old infrastructure laid out from the ancient Greeks.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/coastal-engineering] The coastal environment produces challenges specific for this branch of engineering: waves, storm surges, tides, tsunamis, sea level changes, sea water and the marine ecosystem.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/coastal-engineering] Most often, in coastal engineering projects there is a need for metocean conditions: local wind and wave climate, as well as statistics for and information on other hydrodynamic quantities of interest.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/coastal-engineering] Also, bathymetry and morphological changes are of direct interest.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/coastal-engineering] In case of studies of sediment transport and morphological changes, relevant properties of the sea bed sediments, water and ecosystem properties are needed.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/coastal-engineering] The occurrence of wave phenomena – like sea waves, swell, tides and tsunamis – require engineering knowledge of their physics, as well as models: both numerical models and physical models.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/coastal-engineering] The practices in present-day coastal engineering are more-and-more based on models verified and validated by experimental data.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/coastal-engineering] Apart from the wave transformations themselves, for the waves coming from deep water into the shallow coastal waters and surf zone, the effects of the waves are important.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/coastal-engineering] Coastal engineering takes place at or near the interface between land and water.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/coastal-engineering] Consequently a significant part of coastal engineering involves underwater construction, particularly for foundations.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/coastal-engineering] Breakwaters, sea walls, harbour structures like jetties, wharves and docks, bridges, tunnels, outfalls and causeways usually involve underwater work.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/coastal-engineering] In recent decades, coastal engineers have favored non-structural solutions, which avoid adverse impacts that are typically cause by structures, such as sea walls, bulkheads, jetties, etc.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/coastal-engineering] These solutions include beach nourishment, marsh restoration/creation, and habitat restoration.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/coastal-engineering] More recently, beneficial use of dredge material, which utilizes material dredged for navigation maintenance to nourish beaches and restore wetlands.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/coastal-engineering] Beneficial use is also employed to increase the elevation of marsh platforms in an attempt to adapt to sea level rise.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/coastal-engineering] Regional sediment management has also become a focus strategy for coastal practitioners.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/coastal-engineering] This essentially uses nearshore sediment sources and knowledge of coastal morphology to identify which accretional features can be harvested to bolster erosional areas, understanding the harvested material will continue to accumulate.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/coastal-engineering] A common regional sediment management option is to dredge ebb and flood shoals to nourish beaches.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/coastal-engineering] Another relevant aspect that coastal engineers need to plan for is the effect of climate change whether that be from water levels rising or temperature changes in the water.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/coastal-engineering] Climate change provokes many unknowns for engineers to navigate.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/coastal-engineering] Scientists (Karvetski, Lambert, Keisler, and Linkov) recognized and developed a methodology that coastal engineers can use to identify different scenarios and how to approach climate change problems through an economical, engineering, and ethical way.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/coastal-engineering] This methodology considers the problem at hand such as sea-level rising or influx of storm frequency and analyzes a solution that considers the different stakeholders.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/coastal-engineering] This decision analysis finds many strategies for coastal engineers to make informed decisions on what infrastructure to implement.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/coastal-engineering] Another group formulated a strategy that combines nature conservation and coastal management.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/coastal-engineering] This strategy consisted of examples of creating marshes that disperse wave energy, while also providing ecosystems for coastal wildlife.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/coastal-engineering] Another concept this group discussed was that coral reefs are natural breakwaters that are slowly being destroyed due to ocean acidification from climate change.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/coastal-engineering] Natural and artificial reefs can be used to lower wave height on an average of 70% reducing the wave energy dispersed onshore.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/coastal-engineering] Dredging refers to the mechanical or hydraulic removal of sediments such as sand, silt, or mud from the floors of oceans, rivers or estuaries in order to maintain boat channels, mitigate surpluses of sediment, to reclaim submerged areas and shoreline preservation.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/coastal-engineering] A common use of dredging is to purposely alter bathymetry which affects sediment transport, wave-current interaction and morphological recovery.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/coastal-engineering] Two different types of dredging are topping, which is to remove sediment from the crest of a sand wave to lower its amplitude, and trough dredging, which removes sediment from the trough between the waves.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/coastal-engineering] Both of these methods change the morphology of the ocean post the dredging process.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/coastal-engineering] Two other strategies are uniform removal which is extracting sediment evenly over the terrain or selective removal which targets specific areas of high relief such as navigational channels while also mitigating against unwanted morphological consequences.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/coastal-engineering] New Satellite optical imagery has become an essential tool for coastal engineering.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/coastal-engineering] This has enabled large-scale observation and analysis of shoreline changes, the transportation of sediment and coastal morphology.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/coastal-engineering] Advances in programs like Google Earth have made it possible for coastal engineers to analyze shorelines and bathymetry from public satellite imagery.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/coastal-engineering] In the future, it is expected that high-resolution imaging and videos from space are going to enhance coastal mapping and data essential for management and modeling.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/coastal-engineering] OpenFOAM is an open-source computational fluid dynamics (CFD) program which allows the simulation of two-phase water/air flows.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/coastal-engineering] A study done by scientists (Pablo Higuera, Javier L.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/coastal-engineering] Losada) analyzed how the program was used to formulate flow through porous breakwater and wave-like interactions.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/coastal-engineering] The program was able to accurately simulate free-surface elevation, different pressure systems, and wave dissipation that was consistent with experimental data.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/coastal-engineering] This program allows for coastal engineers to model coastal processes such as wave formation accurately which can be used for designs.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/coastal-engineering] AI is a tool that coastal engineers have started to implement in their practices, especially when it comes to modeling.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/coastal-engineering] Programs such as physics-informed machine learning (PIML) are being integrated to address the different challenges that climate change, sea level rising, and extreme weather pose.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/coastal-engineering] These systems categorize AI applications across different subdomains such as wave modeling, predicting shoreline change, sediment transport, and structural integrity.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/coastal-engineering] The different challenges with using these models is the scarce amount of data available, inability to detect new patterns, and the lack of adaptation for different uncertainties.
[src:asce-asme-journal-of-risk-and-uncertainty-in-engineering-systems/coastal-engineering] However it shows promise within the next decade to improve its predictive capacity and support for decision making within coastal engineering.
